<div>
<div class="block-header"><span class="block-label">Block A</span><span class="block-title">Company Overview</span></div>

<div class="section">
  <div class="section-header"><span class="section-num">1</span><span class="section-title">Company Facts</span></div>
  <div class="section-body">
    <table class="data-table">
      <tr><td style="width:200px;font-weight:600;">Company Name</td><td>Next plc (<a href="https://www.nextplc.co.uk" class="source-link">nextplc.co.uk</a>)</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-weight:600;">Headquarters</td><td>Enderby, Leicestershire, England, UK</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-weight:600;">Year Founded</td><td>1864 (as J. Hepworth &amp; Son); rebranded as Next in 1982</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-weight:600;">CEO / Leadership</td><td>Lord Simon Wolfson (CEO since 2001)</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-weight:600;">Employee Size</td><td>~32,324 (Source: appsruntheworld.com)</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-weight:600;">Revenue (FY2025 ending Jan 2026)</td><td>~£6bn+ group sales; TTM ~$7.60 billion USD (Source: stockanalysis.com/quote/lon/NXT/revenue)</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-weight:600;">Pre-tax Profit</td><td>~£980m statutory profit before tax FY2025; previous year £918m (Source: nextplc.co.uk Annual Report Jan 2025)</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-weight:600;">Company Type</td><td>Public — listed on London Stock Exchange, constituent of FTSE 100</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-weight:600;">Stores</td><td>~500 UK stores; ~200 international franchise stores across 34 countries (Source: Wikipedia / nextplc.co.uk Corporate Responsibility Report Jan 2025)</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-weight:600;">Products / Platforms</td><td>Next Own Brand (clothing, footwear, homeware); Next Label (marketplace for 1,000+ third-party brands); Total Platform (B2B retail infrastructure); Next Finance (nextpay credit, pay in 3); nextunlimited (delivery subscription)</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="sources-block">
      <div class="sources-label">Sources</div>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://www.nextplc.co.uk/~/media/Files/N/next-plc-v4/about-next/annual-report-and-accounts-jan-2025.pdf">nextplc.co.uk — Annual Report Jan 2025</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Next_plc">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Next_plc</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://stockanalysis.com/quote/lon/NXT/revenue/">stockanalysis.com — NXT Revenue</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://www.appsruntheworld.com/customers-database/customers/view/next-plc-united-kingdom">appsruntheworld.com — Next plc Technology Profile</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section" style="margin-top:12px;">
  <div class="section-header"><span class="section-num">2</span><span class="section-title">Company History &amp; Background</span></div>
  <div class="section-body">
    <p class="para">Next plc traces its origins to 1864 when Joseph Hepworth founded J. Hepworth &amp; Son in Leeds as a men's tailoring business. The modern Next brand was created in 1982 under George Davies, pivoting to aspirational coordinated womenswear and establishing the template for a new kind of UK high street fashion retailer. <span class="cite">(Source: en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Next_plc; matrixbcg.com)</span></p>
    <p class="para">Next pioneered the home shopping catalogue model in the 1980s (Next Directory), establishing a direct-to-consumer channel that predated e-commerce by a decade. This catalogue DNA evolved directly into its now-dominant online business. Under Lord Simon Wolfson's leadership since 2001, Next has undergone a sustained transformation from traditional retailer into a multi-faceted platform business, launching Total Platform in 2020 to offer retail-as-a-service to third-party brands. <span class="cite">(Source: internetretailing.net; marketscreener.com)</span></p>
    <p class="para">The company has executed an aggressive acquisition strategy in recent years, taking majority stakes in Reiss, FatFace, and Joules — rescuing distressed retailers and migrating them onto its platform infrastructure. As of 2025, over 800 stores operate under the Next group umbrella across the UK and Ireland, including concessions and standalone stores for acquired brands. <span class="cite">(Source: nextplc.co.uk Corporate Responsibility Report Jan 2025; retailgazette.co.uk)</span></p>
    <div class="sources-block">
      <div class="sources-label">Sources</div>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Next_plc">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Next_plc</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://internetretailing.net/nexts-online-strategy-pays-off-with-fourth-profit-upgrade-in-eight-months/">internetretailing.net</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://www.retailgazette.co.uk/blog/2025/08/how-big-is-nexts-growing-retail-empire/">retailgazette.co.uk — Next's growing retail empire</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section" style="margin-top:12px;">
  <div class="section-header"><span class="section-num">3</span><span class="section-title">Industry &amp; Market Context</span></div>
  <div class="section-body">
    <p class="para">Next operates in UK fashion and homeware retail — the largest clothing retailer by sales in the United Kingdom, having overtaken Marks &amp; Spencer in 2012 and again in 2014. <span class="cite">(Source: en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Next_plc)</span> The UK fashion retail market continues to be shaped by the shift to online — Next's online channel now accounts for over 60% of total group sales, with physical stores stabilising as Click &amp; Collect hubs and brand showrooms. <span class="cite">(Source: nextplc.co.uk Annual Report Jan 2025)</span></p>
    <p class="para">The UK loyalty programme market is intensifying across fashion retail. New Look launched its first-ever loyalty scheme, Club New Look, in 2025 following a £30m digital investment. <span class="cite">(Source: retailgazette.co.uk/blog/2025/10/new-look-loyalty-programme)</span> M&amp;S transformed its Sparks programme in 2025, replacing points with cash rewards in response to customer research demanding "pounds, not points and tricksy pricing." <span class="cite">(Source: corporate.marksandspencer.com/newsroom/press-releases/ms-announces-transformed-sparks-loyalty-programme)</span> Next currently operates no formal loyalty programme for non-credit customers — a structural gap as competitors accelerate.</p>
    <p class="para">Macro headwinds including National Insurance increases (April 2025) added a £25m cost pressure to Next's retail stores P&amp;L in FY2026. <span class="cite">(Source: nextplc.co.uk Annual Report Jan 2026)</span> Despite this, full price sales grew +3.5% YoY, demonstrating resilient consumer demand for Next's core product offer.</p>
    <div class="sources-block">
      <div class="sources-label">Sources</div>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://corporate.marksandspencer.com/newsroom/press-releases/ms-announces-transformed-sparks-loyalty-programme">corporate.marksandspencer.com — M&S Sparks Transformation</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://www.retailgazette.co.uk/blog/2025/10/new-look-loyalty-programme">retailgazette.co.uk — New Look Club loyalty launch</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://www.nextplc.co.uk/~/media/Files/N/next-plc-v4/about-next/annual-report-and-accounts-jan-2026.pdf">nextplc.co.uk — Annual Report Jan 2026</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section" style="margin-top:12px;">
  <div class="section-header"><span class="section-num">4</span><span class="section-title">Product / Platform Overview</span></div>
  <div class="section-body">
    <p class="para">Next's core product is a vertically integrated fashion and homeware retail offer spanning own-brand and third-party labels. The primary channels are next.co.uk (full product catalogue, wishlist, credit account management), the Next mobile app (barcode scanning, Click &amp; Collect booking, order tracking — currently undergoing native app replatform confirmed February 2025), and 500+ UK physical stores. <span class="cite">(Source: retailtechinnovationhub.com — Feb 2025; nextplc.co.uk Corporate Responsibility Report Jan 2025)</span></p>
    <p class="para">Next Finance (nextpay) is a FCA-regulated consumer credit product allowing spread payments, carrying a representative 29.9% APR variable. nextpay is the only current mechanism through which Next rewards customers — holders receive VIP Sale early access (priority shopping slots) exclusively. The nextpay credit book exceeded £1.3 billion by 2025. <span class="cite">(Source: next.co.uk/credit; matrixbcg.com)</span></p>
    <p class="para">Total Platform is Next's B2B retail infrastructure service, leasing website, warehousing, distribution, and contact centre capabilities to third-party brands at a commission of approximately 35–40%. Current Total Platform clients include Reiss, FatFace, Joules, JoJo Maman Bébé, and Made.com among others — seven clients as of January 2024. <span class="cite">(Source: markets.financialcontent.com — March 2026; theindustry.beauty — March 2024)</span></p>
    <div class="sources-block">
      <div class="sources-label">Sources</div>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://retailtechinnovationhub.com/home/2025/2/9/fashion-and-homeware-retailer-next-set-to-replatform-mobile-commerce-offering-to-native-app">retailtechinnovationhub.com — App Replatform Feb 2025</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://www.next.co.uk/credit">next.co.uk/credit — nextpay terms</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://markets.financialcontent.com/stocks/article/finterra-2026-3-2-the-digital-landlord-how-next-plc-nxtl-mastered-the-retail-transformation">markets.financialcontent.com — March 2026</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section" style="margin-top:12px;">
  <div class="section-header"><span class="section-num">5</span><span class="section-title">Business / Revenue Model</span></div>
  <div class="section-body">
    <p class="para">Next generates revenue across four primary streams: (1) Retail stores — 500+ UK locations selling clothing, footwear, home products and third-party brand concessions; (2) Online — next.co.uk and the Next app, accounting for 60%+ of total group sales with UK online net margin of 17.5% (FY2025); (3) Next Finance — consumer credit (nextpay, pay in 3) with a lending book exceeding £1.3bn by 2025, contributing high-margin recurring income; (4) Total Platform — B2B infrastructure services at ~35–40% commission on partner brand sales. <span class="cite">(Source: nextplc.co.uk Annual Report Jan 2025; matrixbcg.com)</span></p>
    <p class="para">Online profit has exceeded retail store profit consistently since 2016, with online delivering approximately £517m profit (FY2024, ending Jan 2024) versus ~£245m from retail stores in the same period. International online sales surged 38.8% in Q3 2025 driven by increased digital marketing and improved product availability on third-party platforms including Zalando. <span class="cite">(Source: statista.com/statistics/980346/next-plc-retail-and-online-sales-profit; internetretailing.net)</span></p>
    <div class="sources-block">
      <div class="sources-label">Sources</div>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://statista.com/statistics/980346/next-plc-retail-and-online-sales-profit">statista.com — Next profit by channel</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://internetretailing.net/nexts-online-strategy-pays-off-with-fourth-profit-upgrade-in-eight-months/">internetretailing.net — Q3 2025 performance</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
</div><!-- /block A -->

<!-- ═══ BLOCK B — MARKET ═══ -->
<div>
<div class="block-header"><span class="block-label">Block B</span><span class="block-title">Market Context</span></div>

<div class="section">
  <div class="section-header"><span class="section-num">6</span><span class="section-title">Loyalty Programme Market — UK Retail</span></div>
  <div class="section-body">
    <p class="para">UK retail loyalty programmes are undergoing structural transformation in 2025. M&amp;S relaunched Sparks in April 2025 with a digital wallet model replacing points — replacing "tricksy pricing" with real cash rewards after customer research identified points complexity as a primary disengagement driver. <span class="cite">(Source: corporate.marksandspencer.com/newsroom — April 2025; marketingweek.com)</span> New Look launched Club New Look in 2025 with a 25% welcome discount, exclusive prices, early sale access, and prize draws following a £30m digital investment. <span class="cite">(Source: retailgazette.co.uk/blog/2025/10/new-look-loyalty-programme)</span></p>
    <p class="para">Industry research indicates 66% of loyalty programme members modify their spending behaviour to maximise point-earning opportunities, and members purchase at up to 2.5× the frequency of non-members. <span class="cite">(Source: cited in secondary research synthesis — Nudge, 2024, referenced in project KB)</span> The current UK loyalty programme landscape is dominated by grocery (Tesco Clubcard, Sainsbury's Nectar) and health &amp; beauty (Boots Advantage Card), with fashion retail lagging — creating an opportunity window for Next. <span class="cite">(Source: statista.com — Most attractive loyalty schemes in Great Britain 2022)</span></p>
    <div class="sources-block">
      <div class="sources-label">Sources</div>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://corporate.marksandspencer.com/newsroom/press-releases/ms-announces-transformed-sparks-loyalty-programme">corporate.marksandspencer.com — M&S Sparks April 2025</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://www.retailgazette.co.uk/blog/2025/10/new-look-loyalty-programme">retailgazette.co.uk — Club New Look 2025</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://whitelabel-loyalty.com/blog/loyalty/the-biggest-changes-and-new-launches-in-loyalty-programs-in-2025">whitelabel-loyalty.com — Loyalty programme changes 2025</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
</div><!-- /block B -->

<!-- ═══ BLOCK C — USERS ═══ -->
<div>
<div class="block-header"><span class="block-label">Block C</span><span class="block-title">Users &amp; Relationships</span></div>

<div class="section">
  <div class="section-header"><span class="section-num">7</span><span class="section-title">Customer Segments (Who Pays)</span></div>
  <div class="section-body">
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Customer Segment</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Core UK Fashion Shopper (Primary)</strong></td><td>Women and men aged 25–55 purchasing clothing, footwear, and accessories across online and in-store channels. Primary revenue driver for own-brand product. High repeat purchase frequency; many holding 10+ year shopping relationships with Next. No current formal loyalty mechanism beyond nextpay for this group. (Source: pitchgrade.com; nextplc.co.uk)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>nextpay Credit Account Holder</strong></td><td>UK customers who have opened a FCA-regulated nextpay or pay in 3 credit account. Receive VIP Sale priority access as a credit benefit. Representative 29.9% APR variable. Existing high-LTV segment. (Source: next.co.uk/credit)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Homeware &amp; Furniture Buyer</strong></td><td>Customers purchasing furniture, soft furnishings, and homeware — often higher basket value, lower purchase frequency. Benefiting from Next's expansion into large-format "department store" style stores combining clothing, home, and third-party brands. (Source: nextplc.co.uk Annual Report)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Third-Party Brand Shopper (Next Label)</strong></td><td>Customers shopping for third-party brands (Nike, Clinique, Reiss, FatFace etc.) via next.co.uk and the Next app. Attracted by the convenience of Next's fulfilment and returns infrastructure for non-Next products. (Source: internetretailing.net)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>International Online Customer</strong></td><td>Customers outside the UK and Ireland purchasing via Next's international online channels and franchise stores across 34 countries. International online sales grew 38.8% in Q3 2025. (Source: internetretailing.net)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <div class="sources-block">
      <div class="sources-label">Sources</div>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://www.next.co.uk/credit">next.co.uk/credit — nextpay terms</a>
      <a class="source-link" href="https://pitchgrade.com/companies/next-plc">pitchgrade.com — Next plc Business Model 2024</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section" style="margin-top:12px;">
  <div class="section-header"><span class="section-num">8</span><span class="section-title">Users in Ecosystem (Who Uses)</span></div>
  <div class="section-body">
    <p class="para" style="font-weight:600;color:var(--navy);">External Users</p>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>User Type</th><th>Responsibility</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Customer</strong></td><td>Browses, purchases, returns, and manages account across web, app, and in-store channels. Would interact with any loyalty programme through all three channels.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>nextpay Account Holder</strong></td><td>As above, plus manages credit account, receives VIP Sale invitations, and uses nextpay in-app card for purchases.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Third-Party Brand Customer</strong></td><td>Shops for partner brands (Reiss, FatFace, etc.) via next.co.uk; uses Next's fulfilment and returns infrastructure.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p class="para" style="font-weight:600;color:var(--navy);margin-top:12px;">Internal Users</p>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>User Type</th><th>Responsibility</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Store Associate</strong></td><td>Operates POS till for purchases, returns, and Click &amp; Collect. Currently has no visibility of customer identity or loyalty status at point of sale. Would be the primary in-store delivery mechanism for any loyalty recognition.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Store Manager</strong></td><td>Oversees in-store operations, associate performance, and store-level metrics. Would govern loyalty programme protocol compliance and recognition standards.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Marketing / CRM Team</strong></td><td>Manages customer communications, promotional campaigns, and VIP Sale coordination. Would design and operate loyalty campaigns and targeted communications.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Next Finance / Credit Team</strong></td><td>Manages the nextpay credit book, FCA compliance, and credit-linked customer benefits. Would govern the boundary between loyalty and credit product functions.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Digital Product Team</strong></td><td>Owns the app and website customer experience. Currently executing the 2025 native app replatform — the technical dependency for any digital loyalty feature delivery.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
