<div class="section">
  <div class="section-body">
    <div class="downstream-item">
      <div class="downstream-agent">User Personas Agent</div>
      <div class="downstream-text">Primary customer segments: (1) Cash/debit shopper — long-tenure, no current loyalty recognition, actively benchmarks loyalty programmes at other retailers (Boots, M&S Sparks), aware of returns penalisation risk; (2) nextpay account holder — receives credit-gated VIP Sale access, high LTV, concerned about loyalty-credit conflation; (3) Store associate — has no POS visibility of customer identity, relies on personal memory for recognition, needs bounded data at the till. Internal users: Marketing/CRM (campaign design), Digital Product (app dependency), Next Finance (FCA boundary management).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="downstream-item">
      <div class="downstream-agent">Design Brief Agent</div>
      <div class="downstream-text">Design problem: Next has no loyalty programme for non-credit customers despite being the UK's largest clothing retailer by sales. Key constraints: (1) FCA regulatory boundary between loyalty and credit (nextpay); (2) native app replatform dependency for QR scanning and push notifications; (3) cross-channel identity fragmentation (nextpay vs online account email mismatch) must be resolved at infrastructure level; (4) GDPR: marketing opt-in must be separated from loyalty enrolment. Key opportunity: extending VIP Sale early access beyond credit holders as a loyalty-earned benefit.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="downstream-item">
      <div class="downstream-agent">Experience Ecosystem Map Agent</div>
      <div class="downstream-text">Key objects: Loyalty Account, Points Balance, Points Transaction, Loyalty Tier, Reward, Early Access Event, Redemption, In-Store Recognition Alert, Programme Rules, Customer Profile, Communication, Integration Log, Next Finance Account, Click &amp; Collect Order, Point Dispute, Manual Adjustment, Physical Card. Key relationships: Purchase → generates Points Transaction; Loyalty Tier → generates In-Store Recognition Alert; Next Finance Account → updates Customer Profile. Critical gap: POS system currently generates zero customer identity output — In-Store Recognition Alert object does not exist in the current system.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="downstream-item">
      <div class="downstream-agent">Experience Roadmap Agent</div>
      <div class="downstream-text">Key journey stages: Programme Discovery (cash customers self-exclude due to credit account assumption); Enrolment (returns data anxiety is enrolment gate — requires plain-English data use statement before CTA); Points Earning — online and in-store (4-second QR scan threshold); Balance &amp; Progress Tracking (permanent home-screen visibility); In-Store Recognition (bounded data: tier, tenure, points only — no purchase history); Early Access Events (loyalty-earned access — the primary enrolment driver); Redemption; Support &amp; Issue Resolution (missed points claims, retrospective earn). Cross-channel continuity is the infrastructure dependency across all stages.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="downstream-item">
      <div class="downstream-agent">UX Requirements Documentation Agent</div>
      <div class="downstream-text">Confirmed technical constraints: (1) Native app replatform in progress 2025 — loyalty must be built on new platform; (2) POS integration required to surface loyalty status to associates; (3) Unified customer identity layer (email + mobile number as backup identifier) required before cross-channel loyalty can function; (4) FCA Consumer Duty compliance — loyalty and credit data must be architecturally separated; (5) GDPR — marketing opt-in separated from loyalty enrolment; (6) Physical card fallback required for non-smartphone users. Key metric: 4-second scan-to-confirmation as technical performance gate for in-store QR interaction.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="downstream-item">
      <div class="downstream-agent">Experience Benchmarking Agent</div>
      <div class="downstream-text">Benchmark programmes: Boots Advantage Card (simplicity gold standard — earn mechanic in one sentence); M&S Sparks (cash wallet model, digital-first, 16m members; recently transformed to address complexity complaints); H&amp;M Member (fashion loyalty entry point — points to cash, early access, low friction); My John Lewis (experience-led rewards, 3.7m members, 2.5× purchase frequency); Pret a Manger / Costa (in-store QR scan speed benchmarks — 4 seconds). Anti-pattern: John Lewis programme restructure without plain-English communication caused member disengagement and lapse.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="downstream-item">
      <div class="downstream-agent">Journey Map Agent</div>
      <div class="downstream-text">Critical journey moments: (1) Enrolment gate — returns data anxiety must be resolved before email submission; (2) First earn — must be visible and real-time at online checkout or in-store scan; (3) First redemption — must occur within first 90 days (domain standard) to prevent lapse; (4) In-store recognition — associate prompt at POS using bounded 3-field display; (5) Early access window — the emotional peak of the programme; (6) Returns and account fragmentation — the primary failure mode when cross-channel identity is not resolved. Key emotion arcs: invisibility (current state) → recognition (enrolment) → accumulation satisfaction → access reward.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
